result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 5th Offense [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] and Operating While Intoxicated - 5th Offense [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)]. The defendant was found guilty of Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 5th Offense [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] and the other charge, Operating While Intoxicated - 5th Offense [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)] was dismissed by the court.

  • Jeffrey Ray Dickson was found guilty of Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 5th Offense [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While under the Influence (5th+ Offense)], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: In the event that the defendant is discharged from probation with outstanding financial obligations, the supervising agent SHALL notify the court 10 days prior to the revocation or discharge.  A civil judgment SHALL be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Any vehicles titled in the Defendant's name and/or any vehicles operated by the Defendant are subject to an ignition interlock device.  The ignition interlock requirement becomes effective when the Defendant applies for a license.
Defendant is to complete an alcohol assessment and comply with any driver safety plan.

miscConds.notes: Defendant is to comply with any treatment/programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and agent.  Defendant is to submit a DNA sample if one has not been previously submitted.
